also been at
the peace table.

09:58.465 --> 10:02.669 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That was one of the very unique,
I think,
features of the Colombia peace
process.

10:02.702 --> 10:07.540 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So they have been working
together with the
guerrillas to come up with these
procedures.

10:07.574 --> 10:11.578 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And this is
still a country
that has a lot of opposition to
the FARC.

10:11.611 --> 10:14.848 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What about the feeling that this
is perhaps
giving them a pass?

10:14.881 --> 10:18.351 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There have been injustices and
human rights
violations on both sides of
this.

10:18.384 --> 10:22.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How do you bring some of those
perpetrators
to justice while you build this
peace?

10:22.088 --> 10:24.257 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CYNTHIA ARNSON: Well, it is
hugely controversial.

10:24.290 --> 10:26.593 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And the country is very
polarized.

10:26.626 --> 10:33.366 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there will be a plebiscite,
a chance for
the Colombian public to vote
either yes or

10:33.399 --> 10:36.803 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
no for the peace accord to be
binding and
valid.

10:36.836 --> 10:41.741 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Thirteen percent -- 50 percent
of 13 percent
of the registered voters have to
come out

10:41.774 --> 10:46.212 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and approve the peace accord
that's been negotiated.

10:46.246 --> 10:53.553 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the most strident critic is
the former
president, Alvaro Uribe, and the
current president,

10:53.586 --> 10:58.391 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Santos, was his defense
minister, and so there
is a tremendous amount of bad
blood.

10:58.424 --> 11:04.831 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there are provisions on
transitional justice
and on the political
participation of the

11:04.864 --> 11:07.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
FARC guerrillas that are really,
really controversial.

11:07.534 --> 11:11.771 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And there is an expression in
Spanish about
swallowing frogs.

11:11.804 --> 11:14.507 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think there are many such
frogs in this
agreement.

11:14.541 --> 11:18.611 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Is there a
possibility here
we could actually see a
campaign, almost a

11:18.645 --> 11:22.782 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
political-style campaign, to try
to encourage
voters to scuttle this accord?

11:22.815 --> 11:27.554 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CYNTHIA ARNSON: Well, that
campaign has been
under way throughout the peace
negotiations.

11:27.587 --> 11:33.726 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A lot of criticism, almost daily
tweets from
President -- former President
Uribe and members

11:33.760 --> 11:35.461 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of his political party.

11:35.495 --> 11:42.001 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There will be a very, very
active campaign
between over -- now and October
2, both by

11:42.035 --> 11:46.439 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the government and its
supporters to mobilize
people to come out and vote in
favor of the

11:46.472 --> 11:52.211 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
accord, and an equally vigorous
campaign by
the opposition to say vote it
down, this is

11:52.245 --> 11:54.080 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
not a good agreement for
Colombia.

11:54.113 --> 11:56.816 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Cynthia Arnson
of the Woodrow
Wilson Center, thanks for
joining us.

11:56.849 --> 11:58.718 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
CYNTHIA ARNSON: Thank you.

11:58.751 --> 12:02.322 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: My
conversation with Cynthia
Arnson continues online on our
Facebook page.

12:02.355 --> 12:06.893 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Viewers also asked her about the
U.S. role
in the conflict, and what
happens if the agreement

12:06.926 --> 12:10.063 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to end the war is rejected in
the referendum.

12:10.096 --> 12:20.139 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You can hear what Cynthia Arnson
has to say
at Facebook.com/NewsHour.

12:20.139 --> 12:25.278 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You can hear what Cynthia Arnson
has to say
at Facebook.com/NewsHour.

12:25.311 --> 12:29.082 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Back in this country, both
presidential candidates
were in full attack mode today.

12:29.115 --> 12:33.519 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At issue, Republican nominee
Donald Trump's
alleged connections to a fringe
conservative

12:33.553 --> 12:34.520 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
philosophy.

12:34.554 --> 12:36.322 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
John Yang has the story.

12:36.356 --> 12:41.527 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Today, Hillary
Clinton debuted
a fresh line of attack against
Donald Trump.

12:41.561 --> 12:44.297 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON (D),
Presidential Candidate:
That is what I want to make
clear today.

12:44.330 --> 12:53.406 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A man with a long history of
racial discrimination,
who traffics in dark conspiracy
theories drawn

12:53.439 --> 13:03.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from the pages of supermarket
tabloids and
the far, dark reaches of the
Internet, should

13:03.750 --> 13:07.887 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
never run our government or
command our military.

13:07.920 --> 13:09.822 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

13:09.856 --> 13:13.092 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: This comes a little
more than a
week after Trump made Steve
Bannon his campaign's

13:13.126 --> 13:14.927 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
CEO.

13:14.961 --> 13:19.999 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Bannon is on leave from his job
as executive
chairman of Breitbart News, a
Web site Bannon

13:20.033 --> 13:24.337 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has called a platform for
something called
the alt- right.

13:24.370 --> 13:29.642 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a movement that lives
largely online,
rejects mainstream conservative
politics,

13:29.676 --> 13:33.913 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and is linked to nationalist and
white supremacist
sentiments.

13:33.946 --> 13:36.249 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Clinton said Trump has echoed
alt-right rhetoric.

13:36.282 --> 13:40.720 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON: All of
this adds up
to something we have never seen
before.

13:40.753 --> 13:49.429 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, of course, there's always
been a paranoid
fringe in our politics, a lot of
arising from

13:49.462 --> 13:51.230 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
racial resentment.

13:51.264 --> 13:56.903 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it's never had the nominee
of a major
party stoking it, encouraging
it, and giving

13:56.936 --> 13:59.972 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it a national megaphone, until
now.

14:00.006 --> 14:05.611 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Clinton's campaign
backed up their
candidate's message online with
this new video

14:05.645 --> 14:09.615 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that includes a Ku Klux Klan
member expressing
support for Trump.

14:09.649 --> 14:11.551 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAN: Donald Trump would be best
for the job.

14:11.584 --> 14:12.552 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
QUESTION: For president?

14:12.585 --> 14:13.553 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
MAN: Yes.

14:13.586 --> 14:14.887 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAN: I am a farmer and white
nationalist.

14:14.921 --> 14:16.089 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Support Donald Trump.

14:16.122 --> 14:18.558 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Even before Clinton
spoke, Trump
hit back.

14:18.591 --> 14:23.463 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP (R), Presidential
Candidate:
When Democratic policies fail,
they are left

14:23.496 --> 14:30.770 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
with only this one tired
argument: You're
racist, you're racist, you're
racist.

14:30.803 --> 14:32.672 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They keep saying it.

14:32.705 --> 14:33.973 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
You're racist.

14:34.006 --> 14:37.677 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It's a tired, disgusting
argument.

14:37.710 --> 14:44.417 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The people of this country who
want their
laws enforced and respected, and
respected

14:44.450 --> 14:50.089 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by all, and who want their
border secured,
are not racists.

14:50.123 --> 14:56.763 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you want to have strong
borders, so that
people come into our country,
but they come

14:56.796 --> 15:01.067 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in legally through a legal
process, that doesn't
make you a racist.

15:01.100 --> 15:03.269 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It makes you smart.

15:03.302 --> 15:06.105 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It makes you an American.

15:06.139 --> 15:13.846 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Today's exchange
between the candidates
shining a spotlight on a
little-known movement.

15:13.880 --> 15:16.349 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, what is the alt-right?

15:16.382 --> 15:19.051 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And how it is influencing this
year's presidential
race?

15:19.085 --> 15:23.956 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For that, we are joined by
Matthew Continetti,
editor in chief of The
Washington Free Beacon,

15:23.990 --> 15:29.262 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a conservative news Web site,
and from Manchester,
New Hampshire, David Weigel, who
covers national

15:29.295 --> 15:31.030 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
politics for The Washington
Post.

15:31.063 --> 15:33.232 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Gentlemen, thank you both for
joining us.

15:33.266 --> 15:36.536 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Dave, let me start with you and
ask you that
question.

15:36.569 --> 15:40.072 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What is alt-right, who's behind
it, where
did it come from?

15:40.106 --> 15:44.844 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID WEIGEL, The Washington
Post: Well, it's
a fair young movement with
fairly old ideas.

15:44.877 --> 15:49.215 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I would say what they're
against, which is
easier to define, is a
philosophy of invite

15:49.248 --> 15:50.583 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the world, invade the world.

15:50.616 --> 15:54.654 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
They are generally
anti-intervention and
anti-multiculturalism.

15:54.687 --> 16:02.662 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they started to grow in
2007, as the Bush
administration was falling to
below 30 percent,

16:02.695 --> 16:08.134 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was seen as discredited, was
obviously going
to help Democrats win the next
election.

16:08.167 --> 16:11.838 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ron Paul's campaign seeded some
of this, but
it really grew under the
presidency of Barack

16:11.871 --> 16:12.839 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Obama.

16:12.872 --> 16:14.607 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And they're fairly young people.

16:14.640 --> 16:16.742 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
This is, I think, what's
worrying for a lot
of progressives and a lot of
people on the

16:16.776 --> 16:22.215 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
right, fairly young people,
under 25, under
30, who have only known the
Republican Party

16:22.248 --> 16:24.183 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
as a disappointment.

16:24.217 --> 16:26.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they have gravitated to
these ideas which
are very anti-immigrant, very
anti-intervention.

16:27.019 --> 16:32.325 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: And they're getting a
lot of attention,
Dave, because of the
anti-Semitic and anti-white

16:32.358 --> 16:35.027 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
-- or -- and white supremacist
rhetoric.

16:35.061 --> 16:39.131 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How central is that to their
message and to
what they believe in?

16:39.165 --> 16:42.368 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID WEIGEL: It's enabled in a
lot of their
messaging.

16:42.401 --> 16:47.673 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Not every alt-right thinker or
activist is
a white nationalist, by far, but
there's a

16:47.707 --> 16:54.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
sense that political correctness
is a bigger
problem than racism, and that
racism is used

16:54.313 --> 16:59.619 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as a cudgel for silencing what
they want to
say, what they want to argue
about.

16:59.652 --> 17:02.154 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's, again, an older idea.

17:02.188 --> 17:06.525 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Before the alt-right, there were
paleoconservatives,
like Sam Francis, like Pat
Buchanan, who argued

17:06.559 --> 17:11.197 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this and said, look, what the
left wants to
do to America, how it wants to
import lots

17:11.230 --> 17:17.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of immigrants, decrease the
number of traditional
white Americans, what they want
to do is not

17:17.570 --> 17:20.940 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
popular, and they have to kind
of Trojan a
horse through culturally, and
we're against

17:20.973 --> 17:21.941 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
that.

17:21.974 --> 17:23.342 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Matthew, what is your
take on this?

17:23.376 --> 17:25.378 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What would you add to that, to
what Dave said?

17:25.411 --> 17:27.880 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MATTHEW CONTINETTI, The
Washington Free Beacon:
I think I have a slightly
narrower definition

17:27.914 --> 17:29.148 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of the alt-right than Dave does.

17:29.181 --> 17:30.983 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

17:31.017 --> 17:33.419 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MATTHEW CONTINETTI: It's true,
there has always
been this kind of critique of
conservatism

17:33.452 --> 17:37.690 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from the non-interventionist,
the non-multicultural
view.

17:37.723 --> 17:41.694 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think the alt-right takes it a
degree further.

17:41.727 --> 17:45.798 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so what you have that
unifies a lot of
these alt-righters on the
Internet is really

17:45.831 --> 17:48.801 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
a disgust at the idea of
egalitarianism.

17:48.834 --> 17:51.537 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They do believe in hierarchies.

17:51.570 --> 17:52.538 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Some of them are racial.

17:52.571 --> 17:54.273 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They also believe in sexual
hierarchies.

17:54.307 --> 17:59.946 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, a lot of them kind of wave
the banner
of the men's rights movement.

17:59.979 --> 18:02.281 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so you start off from that
political conclusion.

18:02.315 --> 18:08.421 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And very quickly, when you read
the rhetoric,
it devolves into just outright
racism, outright

18:08.454 --> 18:10.222 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
misogyny.

18:10.256 --> 18:15.194 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So part of it starts with these
ideas of Sam
Francis, Joe Sobran, Pat
Buchanan, that have

18:15.227 --> 18:18.764 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
been around since the end of the
Cold War,
really.

18:18.798 --> 18:24.870 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But a lot now of it is now much
more visceral,
hatred of the mainstream
cultural movement

18:24.904 --> 18:30.876 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for embracing some version of
egalitarianism,
civil rights, equality of the
sexes.

18:30.910 --> 18:36.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: And, David, what is
the link, or
is there a link or is there a
connection between

18:36.282 --> 18:38.684 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the Trump campaign and the
alt-right?

18:38.718 --> 18:41.787 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID WEIGEL: Well, there always
has been.

18:41.821 --> 18:48.160 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There been alt-right support for
Trump mostly
manifested online or even
sometimes the T-shirts

18:48.194 --> 18:49.595 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and signs you see at rallies.

18:49.628 --> 18:53.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
There is a big alt-right
presence on sites
like 4chan and Reddit.

18:53.899 --> 18:56.836 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it was good that Matt
mentioned the men's
rights movement.

18:56.869 --> 18:58.504 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You could mention Gamergate.

18:58.537 --> 19:01.507 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That was kind of a gateway for a
lot of activists
who consider themselves
alt-right.

19:01.540 --> 19:03.909 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, they supported Trump in the
first place.

19:03.943 --> 19:09.682 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The more direction came when
Steve Bannon,
the CEO of Breitbart, became the
CEO of Trump's

19:09.715 --> 19:11.484 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
campaign.

19:11.517 --> 19:16.355 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Breitbart, very, I think, in a
calculated
and then also in a natural way
became a forum

19:16.389 --> 19:21.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for alt-right thinking and
alt-right coverage,
coverage of politics the way
that those 4chan

19:21.494 --> 19:23.763 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and Reddit people wanted it
covered.

19:23.796 --> 19:27.767 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's when this connection
became harder
to deny and when I think the
Clinton campaign

19:27.800 --> 19:29.635 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
thought it was something to
exploit.

19:29.668 --> 19:34.240 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: And, Matthew, what
does this mean
for the future of the
conservative movement?

19:34.273 --> 19:38.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MATTHEW CONTINETTI: I think it's
one more
sign that conservatism as we
understand it

19:38.077 --> 19:42.014 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is coming under great strain
during the era
of Trump.

19:42.048 --> 19:47.019 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so you have all of these
criticisms of
the mainstream conservatism
represented by

19:47.053 --> 19:49.789 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
William F. Buckley and Ronald
Reagan.

19:49.822 --> 19:53.626 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
All these critics now feel
empowered with
the rise of Donald Trump.

19:53.659 --> 19:57.329 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Anyone who had a bone to pick
with the George
