29:03.642 --> 29:05.510 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PETER NAVARRO: That's right.

29:05.544 --> 29:10.082 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And, of course, if
that's a negative
number, that is, you have more
imports than

29:10.115 --> 29:11.083 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
exports.

29:11.116 --> 29:12.117 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PETER NAVARRO: This is the big
kahuna.

29:12.150 --> 29:14.086 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This is what Donald Trump
understands.

29:14.119 --> 29:15.587 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This is the trade deficit.

29:15.621 --> 29:19.391 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We run a trade deficit of close
to $800 billion
a year.

29:19.424 --> 29:22.928 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so this directly subtracts
from this.

29:22.961 --> 29:25.030 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This is why we're stuck in
low-growth mode.

29:25.063 --> 29:26.565 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Well, maybe.

29:26.598 --> 29:29.368 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
The job of a journalist,
however, is to ask
questions.

29:29.401 --> 29:31.837 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What is U.S. GDP 2016?

29:31.870 --> 29:33.572 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
COMPUTER VOICE: Checking on
that.

29:33.605 --> 29:36.008 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Happily, there's
now Siri to
answer them.

29:36.041 --> 29:39.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
COMPUTER VOICE: It looks like
the answer is
about 18.2 trillion U.S. dollars
per year.

29:39.811 --> 29:41.980 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Thank you, Siri.

29:42.014 --> 29:49.187 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In that case, GDP is something
like $18 trillion,
right?

29:49.221 --> 29:57.129 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you're saying that the trade
deficit is
-- well, it's less than $1
trillion, right?

29:57.162 --> 30:02.801 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, this can't be a major factor
in total
GDP, the size of the economy.

30:02.834 --> 30:07.072 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PETER NAVARRO: Yes, but when we
run these
big trade deficits and send our
jobs offshore,

30:07.105 --> 30:10.208 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we hold our wages down and our
income down.

30:10.242 --> 30:14.346 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That feeds right back into the
biggest part
of this whole equation,
consumption.

30:14.379 --> 30:16.081 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This drags GDP down as well.

30:16.114 --> 30:18.216 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Or so this story
goes.

30:18.250 --> 30:24.222 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When you hear the criticism
about Donald Trump's
own goods being made in other
countries, what's

30:24.256 --> 30:25.223 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
your reaction?

30:25.257 --> 30:26.358 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PETER NAVARRO: Do me a favor.

30:26.391 --> 30:28.560 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Play Dan Slane's clip in my
"Death by China"
movie.

30:28.593 --> 30:30.429 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's priceless.

30:30.462 --> 30:34.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Slane was a plywood
manufacturer
in Bowling Green, Kentucky,
whose competitors

30:34.299 --> 30:36.001 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
moved to China.

30:36.034 --> 30:38.870 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAN SLANE, Business Owner: And I
opened up
three factories in China and
delivered to

30:38.904 --> 30:43.475 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the customer in the United
States 50 percent
cheaper than I could make it in
Bowling Green.

30:43.508 --> 30:47.512 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PETER NAVARRO: He winds up
selling product
back here into the U.S. at cost.

30:47.546 --> 30:49.381 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
How did he make his money?

30:49.414 --> 30:54.086 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAN SLANE: Every month, the
Chinese government
would send me a check for 17
percent of my

30:54.119 --> 30:57.589 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
exports, and that was my net
margin and my
profit.

30:57.622 --> 31:00.792 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So, is Donald Trump
getting checks
from the Chinese government?

31:00.826 --> 31:01.893 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PETER NAVARRO: That's how the
game works.

31:01.927 --> 31:05.731 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But he could use
American companies.

31:05.764 --> 31:11.903 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are lots of people who
actually say
made in USA and use that as a
marketing tool.

31:11.937 --> 31:13.805 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PETER NAVARRO: The point here
is, he can't.

31:13.839 --> 31:21.046 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The competitive forces that
force a Dan Slane
to take his furniture company to
China, they're

31:21.079 --> 31:22.848 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
real, OK?

31:22.881 --> 31:27.419 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if you try and take the high
ground and
produce here in America, when
China's dumping

31:27.452 --> 31:31.523 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
product in and manipulating
their currency,
you go out of business.

31:31.556 --> 31:33.024 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You just go out of business.

31:33.058 --> 31:38.630 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: What about the
character issues
that surround Donald Trump?

31:38.663 --> 31:42.768 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PETER NAVARRO: Well, look, I
don't go there.

31:42.801 --> 31:44.636 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I focus on policy.

31:44.669 --> 31:46.004 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That's my job.

31:46.037 --> 31:49.374 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And you have no
problem with
the failed companies?

31:49.407 --> 31:54.312 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PETER NAVARRO: No one should be
surprised
just because somebody isn't
successful 100

31:54.346 --> 31:55.547 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
percent of the time.

31:55.580 --> 31:59.484 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
The percent here, he's a
billionaire.

31:59.518 --> 32:01.219 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
He's successful.

32:01.253 --> 32:07.659 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And no matter how
much money
he actually has or hasn't got,
given that

32:07.692 --> 32:12.898 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Donald Trump is the Republican
candidate for
president of the United States,
no can argue

32:12.931 --> 32:17.469 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that he isn't successful -- to
date, at least.

32:17.502 --> 32:23.308 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
"NewsHour" economics
correspondent Paul Solman,
reporting from Irvine,
California.

32:23.341 --> 32:28.246 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And next week,
Paul will
look at Hillary Clinton's
approach to trade,

32:28.280 --> 32:41.293 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and how she has changed over
time.

32:41.326 --> 32:45.730 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now a conversation with one of
the biggest
stars of this summer's Olympics,
Gold medal-winning

32:45.764 --> 32:49.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
swimmer Katie Ledecky, about
what's behind
her success.

32:49.034 --> 32:51.169 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Margaret Warner sat down with
her earlier
today.

32:51.203 --> 32:57.008 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: She's been
likened to a Lamborghini,
to a hard-charging swimming
machine.

32:57.042 --> 33:03.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Katie Ledecky, the freestyle
phenom, won five
medals in Rio, four gold, one
silver.

33:03.748 --> 33:06.718 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Also remarkable is her dominance
in her sport.

33:06.751 --> 33:12.457 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In this 800-meter race in Rio,
for example,
her closest competitor was
nearly a pool-length

33:12.491 --> 33:14.593 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
away.

33:14.626 --> 33:20.565 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ledecky's Olympic debut came at
age 15 in
the 2012 London Games, when she
defeated the

33:20.599 --> 33:24.302 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
favorite, a British gold
medalist, to win
the 800.

33:24.336 --> 33:28.807 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now 19, she repeatedly breaks
world records,
usually her own.

33:28.840 --> 33:30.609 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

33:30.642 --> 33:35.513 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Ledecky is
known not just
for her relentless training,
more than four

33:35.547 --> 33:40.952 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
hours a day, but for her
friendliness, calm
and modesty.

33:40.986 --> 33:44.789 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Amid the celebrations since her
return to
Washington, last night, she
threw out the

33:44.823 --> 33:47.592 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
first pitch at the Washington
Nationals Game.

33:47.626 --> 33:50.228 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MAN: Oh, great pitch.

33:50.262 --> 33:57.369 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Now she's
taking an unusual
path for such a proven winner,
retain her

33:57.402 --> 34:03.174 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
amateur status, attend Stanford
this fall,
and pass for the moment on
millions of dollars

34:03.208 --> 34:05.243 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of endorsement deals.

34:05.277 --> 34:09.948 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We got together today at the
pool where she
competed in high school, Stone
Ridge School

34:09.981 --> 34:13.585 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of the Sacred Heart in Bethesda,
Maryland.

34:13.618 --> 34:14.586 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Katie Ledecky, welcome.

34:14.619 --> 34:15.820 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Thank you for joining us.

34:15.854 --> 34:17.355 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATIE LEDECKY, U.S. Olympic Gold
Medal Winner:
Thank you.

34:17.389 --> 34:19.658 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Or letting us
join you at
your old stomping ground here.

34:19.691 --> 34:24.229 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Something that struck me
watching you swim,
but also out of the pool, is
just this joy

34:24.262 --> 34:25.363 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
you seem to radiate.

34:25.397 --> 34:27.699 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KATIE LEDECKY: I have always
loved swimming.

34:27.732 --> 34:31.469 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I started swimming when I was 6
years old
for a summer league swim team.

34:31.503 --> 34:35.206 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they made it really fun
right from day
one.

34:35.240 --> 34:36.875 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And I never really looked back.

34:36.908 --> 34:41.913 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I started swimming year-round,
and did it
with my family, with my friends,
and just

34:41.947 --> 34:44.115 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have gotten to meet so many
great people through
swimming.

34:44.149 --> 34:47.385 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: And I was
surprised to see
that, in 2012, when you went to
the Olympic

34:47.419 --> 34:53.091 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
training camp, they gave you
some elite athlete
tests just on your physical
abilities.

34:53.124 --> 34:55.093 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And it came back saying
remarkably unremarkable.

34:55.126 --> 34:56.094 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

34:56.127 --> 34:57.495 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: What does that
mean?

34:57.529 --> 35:02.901 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
KATIE LEDECKY: I'm not
ridiculously tall for
swimmers.

35:02.934 --> 35:04.736 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I don't have very big hands.

35:04.769 --> 35:07.639 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I don't have very big feet,
nothing really
unusual.

35:07.672 --> 35:11.343 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think it's just been hard work
that's gotten
me to where I am today.

35:11.376 --> 35:13.745 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It wasn't a lot of talent,
really.

35:13.778 --> 35:19.718 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was more getting through the
work and setting
some big goals that has gotten
me to this

35:19.751 --> 35:20.719 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
point.

35:20.752 --> 35:21.720 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Do you enjoy
working hard?

35:21.753 --> 35:23.121 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
KATIE LEDECKY: I do.

35:23.154 --> 35:26.524 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's fun when you get to do
it with some
of your best friends.

35:26.558 --> 35:27.993 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And that's what I have loved.

35:28.026 --> 35:32.030 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I have just loved setting big
goals and trying
to reach towards them.

35:32.063 --> 35:36.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, a couple of years ago, my
coach, Bruce
Gemmell, and I sat down and set
some goals.

35:36.601 --> 35:41.940 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And at the time, they seemed
pretty big, but
I reached them all in Rio, and
that's the

35:41.973 --> 35:43.675 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
best feeling.

35:43.708 --> 35:46.678 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: And the goals
are about not
beating someone else, but about
times.

35:46.711 --> 35:48.446 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
KATIE LEDECKY: Right.

35:48.480 --> 35:55.820 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My goals for Rio were to go 3:56
or better
in the 400 free, and I went
3:56, to go 8:05

35:55.854 --> 35:59.424 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
or better in the 800 free, and I
went 8:04.

35:59.457 --> 36:01.659 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then the third goal was to
win the 200
free.

36:01.693 --> 36:02.727 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
And I did that.

36:02.761 --> 36:05.563 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, I matched all my goals.

36:05.597 --> 36:09.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And at the time, three years
ago, those seemed
pretty far out there.

36:09.234 --> 36:12.404 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: To what degree
are you competing
with others vs. yourself?

36:12.437 --> 36:18.009 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATIE LEDECKY: You are always
racing against
the other swimmers, but I always
try to just

36:18.043 --> 36:20.779 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
focus on what I'm doing and how
I want to
swim my races.

36:20.812 --> 36:23.548 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MARGARET WARNER: Are you
checking out what's
going on in the other lanes?

36:23.581 --> 36:25.116 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
KATIE LEDECKY: I sometimes do.

36:25.150 --> 36:27.986 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And if I'm ahead, I can
sometimes tell.

36:28.019 --> 36:33.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It might mean I'm having a good
swim, but
pretty much, I'm just focused on
how fast

36:33.658 --> 36:38.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm going, how fast I'm feeling,
and pretty
much block everything out, the
sounds, the

36:38.730 --> 36:42.801 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
sights, just kind of listen to
the rhythm
of the water, and just
maintaining the same

36:42.834 --> 36:47.806 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
stroke, the same rhythm, the
same tempo, and
thinking about how I want to get
my hand to

36:47.839 --> 36:49.607 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the wall.

36:49.641 --> 36:52.343 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: David Marsh,
who is the coach
of the whole U.S. team, Olympic
team, said

36:52.377 --> 36:58.183 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you had an intensity that he'd
never seen
in a distance athlete, and that
you were fearless.

36:58.216 --> 37:02.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Another coach of yours said
that, put you
at the beginning of a race, and
you're like

37:02.387 --> 37:05.256 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a bull in a stall waiting to get
out.

37:05.290 --> 37:06.891 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Where does that come from?

37:06.925 --> 37:08.927 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
KATIE LEDECKY: I don't know.

37:08.960 --> 37:13.031 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think I have always loved the
competitiveness
of swimming.

37:13.064 --> 37:17.969 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I have just had that outlet
from since
I was 6 years old.

37:18.002 --> 37:21.072 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I think it's something
that's developed
over time, too.

37:21.106 --> 37:26.511 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As I have gotten faster and I
have come down
to some of the shorter races,
the sprint events,

37:26.544 --> 37:31.483 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have always just tried to have
that mind-set
of attacking each race and
really treating

37:31.516 --> 37:35.120 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
each race, no matter how long it
is, as a
true race.

37:35.153 --> 37:38.056 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: And that's why
you don't
pace yourself, the way a lot of
coaches would

37:38.089 --> 37:39.057 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
advise you to do?

37:39.090 --> 37:40.058 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
KATIE LEDECKY: Right.

37:40.091 --> 37:41.192 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

37:41.226 --> 37:43.128 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I like to think of it more as
racing than
pacing.

37:43.161 --> 37:45.964 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: A lot of top
athletes, especially
when they reach even near the
pinnacle you

37:45.997 --> 37:50.802 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have, talk about the pressure
they feel, and
that they feel anxiety to
perform.

37:50.835 --> 37:52.837 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Do you ever feel that?

37:52.871 --> 37:54.672 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
KATIE LEDECKY: No, I don't.

37:54.706 --> 38:00.345 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I always just focus on what my
own goals are,
and not what anybody else's
goals for me are

38:00.378 --> 38:02.113 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
or their expectations.

38:02.147 --> 38:06.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I just know that my family will
always be
supporting me and my friends and
my coaches.

