Wheelchair New York
by night and clinical
psychologist by day.

50:16.747 --> 50:18.382 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I'm on Tinder.

50:18.415 --> 50:20.251 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm out there dating.

50:20.284 --> 50:26.190 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It really supplements what I do
as a clinician,
because I know exactly what my
patients with

50:26.223 --> 50:28.726 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
disabilities encounter.

50:28.759 --> 50:34.965 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
People have asked me many times
online dating,
can you function sexually?

50:34.999 --> 50:38.002 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And I always answer back, yes.

50:38.035 --> 50:39.770 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Can you?

50:39.803 --> 50:43.941 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I remember, when I first moved
to New York
and started dating, I was just,
you know,

50:43.974 --> 50:52.650 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
being rejected, having
inappropriate questions
asked about me, like, oh, hi,
what's your

50:52.683 --> 50:53.617 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
name?

50:53.651 --> 50:55.519 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Oh, can you have sex?

50:55.552 --> 50:59.056 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You know, you really don't start
out conversations
like that.

50:59.089 --> 51:03.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The problem lies in the fact
that we don't
see a lot of people with
disability in the

51:03.594 --> 51:05.329 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
media.

51:05.362 --> 51:09.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One night, I got a call from my
friend who
said: Hey, I found this pageant
online, the

51:09.733 --> 51:11.201 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Ms. Wheelchair New York Pageant.

51:11.235 --> 51:16.173 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I thought to myself, let me
do that pageant,
and let me try and win it.

51:16.206 --> 51:18.075 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
If I could wear high heels, then
they can.

51:18.108 --> 51:22.713 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If I can dress sexy or do my
hair, then they
can do it, too.

51:22.746 --> 51:30.754 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are numerous stereotypes
that are still
associated with disability,
being asexual,

51:30.788 --> 51:35.492 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
being unable to have sex, we
don't make good
romantic partners.

51:35.526 --> 51:41.231 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So the notion of sex in society
that we see
on TV, it often shows these
physically fit

51:41.265 --> 51:44.435 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
people having traditional forms
of sex.

51:44.468 --> 51:49.873 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You don't have to be able to do
the standard
throw-down notions of sex.

51:49.907 --> 51:50.975 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Anything can be sexy.

51:51.008 --> 51:54.345 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It could be a fluttering eyelash
on a cheek.

51:54.378 --> 52:00.184 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When you don't see yourself in
those magazines
or part of those models, then
you internalize

52:00.217 --> 52:04.488 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that image and think that, OK, I
guess I'm
not sexy.

52:04.521 --> 52:09.760 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
People with disabilities have
the same sexual
needs and desires and appetite
for romance

52:09.793 --> 52:12.963 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and intimacy that everyone else
has.

52:12.997 --> 52:15.866 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's part of being human.

52:15.899 --> 52:22.473 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My name is Dr. Danielle Sheypuk,
and this
is my Brief But Spectacular take
on making

52:22.506 --> 52:24.675 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
disability sexy.

